It appears that young adults (27-30) and middle age adults (40-48) make the largest amount of income
Similiarly, young adults (24-30) and middle age adults (40-47) also use the treadmill most
This should mean that we should ofcus efforts on these two groups. We can now look at the opposite, which age groups are likely to be the smallest contribution

In [19]:



    


Cardio.groupby(by=['Age'])['Usage'].mean().reset_index().sort_values(['Usage']).head(10).plot(x='Age', y='Usage', kind='bar', figsize=(15,5))
plt.show()



    















    




























It seems that very young adults (18-26) and older but not middle age adults (36-37) have the lowest income
The least usage appears amongst very young adults (18-20) older but not middle age adults (37) and older middle aged adults (43-50) but this difference seems to be minor in both cases.
So while there may be minor age difference in usage, we may not want to use it as a major targetting indicator
